Weather Data Analysis with Python Pandas in Jupyter Notebook  
· Exploratory Data Analysis over 70280 data elements answering different questions 
Functions performed: 
· File import in Jupyter using pd.read_csv(). 
· Dataframe analysis using head(), shape. 
· Dataframe index fetching using .index. 
· Dataframe column fetching using .columns. 
· Column-wise datatype fetching using .dtypes. 
· Single column unique values fetching using .unique(). 
· Column-wise no. of unique values fetching using .nunique(). 
· Column-wise no. of null values fetching using .count(). 
· Single column count of each unique value fetching using .value_counts(). 
· Dataframe basic information fetching using .info(). 
· Filtering to return all columns when weather is exactly clear. 
· Grouping to return all columns when weather is exactly clear. 
· Filtering to return all columns when wind speed is exactly 4 km/hr. 
· Finding out all null values in data using .isnull(). 
· Finding out total no. of null values in data using .isnull.sum(). 
· Finding out non-null values in data using .notnull().sum(). 
· Renaming column name using .rename() and inplace. 
· Calculating mean visibility using .mean(). 
· Calculating standard deviation of pressure using .std(). 
· Calculating variance of Relative Humidity using .var(). 
· Finding all instances where Snow was recorded using filtering. 
· Finding instances having ‘Snow’ in their names using str.contains(). 
· Finding first and last instances having ‘Snow’ using .head() and .tail(). 
· Finding all instances where speed is above 24 and visibility is 25 using filtering with ‘&’ operator. 
· Finding mean value of each column against Weather Condition using groupby()  and mean(). 
· Finding min. and max. of each column against ‘Weather Condition’ using groupby(), .min() and .max(). 
· Showing all records where weather condition is Fog using filtering. 
· Finding all instances where 'Weather is clear' or 'Visibility is above 40' using filtering with ‘|’ operator. 
· Finding all instances where 'Weather is clear' and 'Relative humidity is greater than 50’ or Visibility is above 40 using filtering and ‘&’ and ‘|’ operator. 
